<doc id="897724" wikidata="Q3229345" url="?curid=897724" title="Schreier's lemma">
<text>In mathematics, Schreier&#x27;s lemma is a theorem in group theory used in the Schreier–Sims algorithm and also for finding a presentation of a subgroup. 

==Statement==

Suppose formula_1 is a subgroup of formula_2, which is finitely generated with generating set formula_3, that is, formula_4. 

Let formula_5 be a right transversal of formula_1 in formula_2. In other words, formula_5 is (the image of) a section of the quotient map formula_9, where formula_10 denotes the set of right cosets of formula_1 in formula_2.

The definition is made given that formula_13, formula_14 is the chosen representative in the transversal formula_5 of the coset formula_16, that is, 
:formula_17

Then formula_1 is generated by the set
:formula_19

Hence, in particular, Schreier&#x27;s lemma implies that every subgroup of finite index of a finitely generated group is again finitely generated.

== Example ==
The group Z3 = Z/3Z is cyclic. Via Cayley&#x27;s theorem, Z3 is a subgroup of the symmetric group &quot;S&quot;3. Now,
: formula_20
: formula_21
where formula_22 is the identity permutation. Note &quot;S&quot;3 = formula_23{ &quot;s&quot;1=(1 2), &quot;s&quot;2 = (1 2 3) }formula_24.

Z3 has just two cosets, Z3 and &quot;S&quot;3 \ Z3, so we select the transversal { &quot;t&quot;1 = &quot;e&quot;, &quot;t&quot;2=(1 2) }, and we have 
: formula_25

Finally, 
: formula_26
: formula_27
: formula_28
: formula_29

Thus, by Schreier&#x27;s subgroup lemma, { e, (1 2 3) } generates Z3, but having the identity in the generating set is redundant, so it can be removed to obtain another generating set for Z3, { (1 2 3) } (as expected).

==References==
* Seress, A. Permutation Group Algorithms. Cambridge University Press, 2002.</text><links>
